description: Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), or lupus, is a chronic, autoimmune disease that can affect many parts of the body. SLE causes the immune system – the body’s natural defense against illness and infection - to create antibodies instead of protecting your body from infection.

description: APIGN, or post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis, occurs as a sequela to infection with certain nephritogenic strains of group A streptococci, most frequently following pharyngitis. Symptoms may be mild and spontaneously resolve. Severe cases can result in long term damage to the glomerular filtration system, with the potential to progress to end-stage kidney disease over months or even years
description:  Henoch-Schonlein purpura or Ig A vasculitis, is a condition that causes small blood vessels in your skin and other organs, such as your kidneys and intestines, to become inflamed.
description:  A rare disorder in which your immune system mistakenly destroys your own red blood cells.

description: A connective tissue disorder in which symptoms and features of several autoimmune diseases, including lupus, scleroderma, polymyositis and rheumatoid arthritis, occur simultaneously or in sequence, and which rarely may progress to an overlap syndrome.

description: An uncommon condition characterized by the combined features of polymyositis (inflammation in multiple muscle tissues and associated weakness) and features of the connective tissue disease scleroderma.
